04625nam a22007575i 9780813593685DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135936857 a10.36019/97808135936852doi  a(DE-B1597)529831  a(OCoLC)1120691871  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aPER0000002bisacsh04a791.43/6162231 aTrimble, S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aUndead Ends :bStories of Apocalypse /cS. Trimble. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©2019  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b15 b-w  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: Storytelling and Survival -- t1. Telling Other Tales: Rememory in The Road -- t2. Adaptations and Mutations: I Am Legend's Double Helix -- t3. Revolting Reanimations: The 28 Films -- t4. Maternal Backgrounds: Children of Men -- t5. Myth and Metamorphosis: Beasts of the Southern Wild -- tEpilogue: After Man, or, Death by Story -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tABOUT THE AUTHOR0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aUndead Ends is about how we imagine humanness and survival in the aftermath of disaster. This book frames modern British and American apocalypse films as sites of interpretive struggle. It asks what, exactly, is ending? Whose dreams of starting over take center stage, and why? And how do these films, sometimes in spite of themselves, make room to dream of new beginnings that don't just reboot the world we know? Trimble argues that contemporary apocalypse films aren't so much envisioning The End of the world as the end of a particular world; not The End of humanness but, rather, the end of Man. Through readings of The Road, I Am Legend, 28 Days Later, 28 Weeks Later, Children of Men, and Beasts of the Southern Wild, this book demonstrates that popular stories of apocalypse can trouble, rather than reproduce, Man's story of humanness. With some creative re-reading, they can even unfold towards unexpected futures. Mainstream apocalypse films are, in short, an occasion to imagine a world After Man.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aApocalypse in motion pictures. 0aApocalyptic filmszGreat BritianxHistory and criticism. 0aApocalyptic filmszUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts 2019z9783110605785oZDB-23-DPK08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2019 Englishz978311061001708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065352640uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/9780813593685zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813593685423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813593685.jpg  a978-3-11-061001-7  EBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-061076-5  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-065352-6  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGGb2019  aZDB-23-DPKb2019